name: Kasbah of the Udayas
description: A historic kasbah in Rabat, known for its white-and-blue painted streets, Andalusian gardens, and views of the Bouregreg River.

name: Mausoleum of Mohammed V
description: A mausoleum in Rabat housing the tombs of King Mohammed V and his sons, known for its stunning architecture and historical significance.

name: Botanical Garden of Rabat
description: A public garden in Rabat, offering a variety of plant species, peaceful pathways, and educational exhibits on local flora.

name: Sindibad Park
description: A family-friendly amusement park offering various rides, attractions, and a zoo, providing entertainment and fun for visitors of all ages.

name: Hermitage Park
description: A tranquil green space in the heart of Casablanca, known for its serene environment, walking paths, and a variety of plant species, ideal for leisurely strolls and relaxation.

name: Casablanca Cathedral
description: Also known as the Sacré-Cœur Cathedral, this stunning example of neo-Gothic architecture was completed in 1930. Although it no longer serves as a place of worship, it hosts cultural events and exhibitions.

name: Isesco Park
description: Named after the Islamic Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (ISESCO), this park provides recreational spaces, playgrounds, and gardens, promoting a peaceful environment for families and visitors.

name: Arab League Park of Casablanca
description: A large urban park established in 1918, featuring lush greenery, walking paths, fountains, and playgrounds, making it a popular spot for both locals and tourists to relax.

name: El Hank Lighthouse
description: Built in 1916, this lighthouse stands at 51 meters tall and provides a vital navigation aid along the Atlantic coast. It offers panoramic views of the ocean and the city.

name: Enclosure of Sour Jdid
description: A historic area featuring remnants of old city walls, it offers a glimpse into Casablanca's past with its traditional architecture and historical significance.

name: Notre-Dame-de-Lourdes Church
description: Notable for its modernist architecture and impressive stained glass windows, this church was completed in 1954 and remains an active place of worship in Casablanca.

name: Cape Spartel Lighthouse
description: A historic lighthouse located at the entrance of the Strait of Gibraltar, offering panoramic views of the Atlantic Ocean and Mediterranean Sea.

name: Tangier Cathedral
description: Also known as St. Andrew's Church, an Anglican cathedral in Tangier, known for its unique blend of Moorish and Gothic architectural styles.

name: Dar el Makhzen (Tangier)
description: A historic palace in Tangier that now houses a museum showcasing Moroccan art, artifacts, and archaeological finds.

name: Grand Socco
description: A large public square in Tangier, serving as a major social and commercial hub, connecting the old Medina with the modern city.

name: Borj Es-Salam
description: A historic fortification in Tangier, notable for its military architecture and strategic location overlooking the city.

name: Abraham Toledano Synagogue
description: A historic synagogue in Tangier, reflecting the rich Jewish heritage and history of the city.

name: Petit Socco
description: A small square in the Medina of Tangier, historically a meeting place for merchants and now a bustling area with cafés and shops.

name: Bab El Bhar (Tangier)
description: A historic gate in Tangier, part of the city's ancient fortifications, offering insight into its defensive architecture.

name: Church of the Immaculate Conception
description: A Catholic church in Tangier, known for its architectural beauty and its role as a place of worship for the local Catholic community.

name: Bab Mahrouk
description: A well-known gate in Fez, historically used for various administrative purposes and recognized for its architectural style.

name: Seffarin Madrasa
description: An Islamic school in Fez, celebrated for its beautiful architecture and significant role in the religious and educational history of the city.

name: Bab Chorfa
description: A historic gate in Fez, known for its striking design and importance as part of the city's ancient fortifications.

name: Bab Dekkakin
description: A gate in Fez with historical significance, connecting different parts of the city and reflecting traditional Moroccan design.

name: Bab el-Semarine
description: One of the main gates of Fez, known for its historical significance and intricate architectural details.

name: Kasbah of Cherarda
description: An old fortress in Fez, originally built for military purposes and now a notable historical site.

name: Medersa Al Mesbahia
description: An Islamic school in Fez known for its stunning architecture, intricate tile work, and historical importance in education.

name: Bab Lhadid
description: A historical gate in Fez, part of the city's ancient walls, known for its architectural beauty.

name: Bab Ftouh
description: A famous gate in Fez, serving as an important entrance to the old city and notable for its historical and architectural value.

name: Bab lkhokha
description: Another historical gate in Fez, featuring traditional Moroccan architectural elements and serving as a key entry point to the old city.

name: Jemaa el-Fnaa
description: The main square in Marrakech, famous for its bustling atmosphere, street performers, food stalls, and vibrant nightlife.

name: Bahia Palace
description: A 19th-century palace in Marrakech, known for its beautiful gardens, elaborate interiors, and stunning examples of Moroccan architecture.

name: Saadian Tombs
description: The royal necropolis in Marrakech, dating back to the Saadian dynasty, famous for its ornate decoration and historical importance.

name: Ben Salah Mosque
description: A historic mosque in Marrakech, notable for its distinctive minaret and its role as a central place of worship in the city.

name: Majorelle Garden
description: A botanical garden in Marrakech, created by French artist Jacques Majorelle, featuring vibrant blue buildings and a variety of exotic plants.

name: El Badi Palace
description: A ruined palace in Marrakech, originally built in the 16th century and known for its grand design and historical significance.

name: Kutubiyya Mosque
description: A landmark mosque in Marrakech, known for its impressive minaret and its significance as one of the largest and oldest mosques in the city.

name: Arsat Moulay Abdessalam Garden
description: A public garden in Marrakech, offering a tranquil green space with various plants, fountains, and walking paths.

name: Bab Aghmat
description: A historical gate in Marrakech, serving as an important entry point to the old medina and known for its architectural details.

name: Heri es-Swani
description: A large granary and stable complex in Meknes, originally built by Moulay Ismail, showcasing impressive engineering and historical importance.

name: El Hedim Square
description: A large public square in Meknes, often compared to Jemaa el-Fnaa, known for its lively atmosphere and surrounding historical sites.

name: Meknes Royal Military Academy
description: A prestigious military academy in Meknes, known for its training programs and historical significance in Moroccan military education.

name: Dar el Kbira
description: A historic residential palace in Meknes, once home to prominent figures, now known for its architectural beauty and cultural heritage.

name: Dar Al Makhzen (Meknes)
description: The Royal Palace in Meknes, serving as a residence for the Moroccan royal family and an important site of governmental activities.

name: Koubat Al Khayatine
description: A historic building in Meknes, used for diplomatic and administrative purposes, notable for its architectural design.

name: Kara Prison
description: A historic underground prison in Meknes, known for its vast, dark chambers and its use during the reign of Moulay Ismail.

name: Bab Mansour
description: A grand gate in Meknes, famous for its intricate decoration and considered one of the most beautiful gates in Morocco.

name: Bou Inania Madrasa
description: A 14th-century Islamic school in Meknes, known for its stunning architecture, intricate tile work, and historical educational significance.

name: Agdal Basin
description: A historic basin in the Agdal Gardens of Marrakech, used for irrigation and providing a picturesque setting among the orchards.

name: El Ablat Borj
description: A historic tower in Morocco, notable for its defensive purpose and architectural features.

name: Kasbah of Ayyir
description: A historic fortress in Morocco, significant for its strategic location and traditional military architecture.

name: Sea Castle
description: A historic coastal fortress in Rabat, offering views of the Atlantic Ocean and significant for its defensive role in the past.

name: Ben Hamidouch Kasba
description: A historical kasbah in Morocco, notable for its traditional architecture and cultural significance.

name: Potters' Quarter
description: A famous district in Safi, known for its traditional pottery workshops and vibrant artisan community.

name: Safi Medina
description: The old town of Safi, featuring traditional markets, historical buildings, and a rich cultural heritage.

name: Souira Qedima Kasbah
description: An ancient kasbah in Morocco, notable for its historical importance and traditional architectural style.

name: Borj Ed-dar (Safi)
description: A historic fortification in Safi, known for its defensive architecture and views over the surrounding area.

name: Borj Souira El Kadima
description: A historic fort in Morocco, recognized for its role in regional defense and its architectural heritage.

name: Sidi Mohammed Salih
description: A historic site or shrine in Morocco, often visited for its cultural and religious significance.

name: Kasbah of Chefchaouen
description: A 15th-century fortress in Chefchaouen, offering a glimpse into the town's history with its traditional architecture and museum.

name: Chefchaouen Church
description: A historic church located in the picturesque blue city of Chefchaouen, reflecting the city's diverse cultural heritage.

name: El-Makhzen Square
description: A prominent public square that serves as a central point in many Moroccan cities, often surrounded by important governmental and administrative buildings.
